"Negri A.P., Flores F., Röthig T., Uthicke S.","Herbicides increase the vulnerability of corals to rising sea surface temperature",2011,"Limnology and Oceanography","56","2",,"471","485",,,10.4319/lo.2011.56.2.0471,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79952054639&partnerID=40&md5=51c55887306629bec23addc32f3bfa09","Australian Institute of Marine Science, Townsville, QLD, Australia","Negri, A.P., Australian Institute of Marine Science, Townsville, QLD, Australia; Flores, F., Australian Institute of Marine Science, Townsville, QLD, Australia; Röthig, T., Australian Institute of Marine Science, Townsville, QLD, Australia; Uthicke, S., Australian Institute of Marine Science, Townsville, QLD, Australia","In order to examine the potential interactive pressures of local pollution and global climate change, we exposed corals and crustose coralline algae (CCA) to three agricultural photosystem II (PSII) herbicides at four temperatures (26-32°C). The coral Acropora millepora was 3- to 10-fold more sensitive to the three herbicides than the CCA Neogoniolithon fosliei. While the photosynthesis of CCA was not affected by the herbicide concentrations used (&lt; 1 μg L-1), temperatures of 31°C and 32°C alone significantly inhibited photosynthetic efficiency (ΔF:F'm) and caused chronic photoinhibition (reduced Fv : Fm) and substantial bleaching. Environmentally relevant concentrations of each herbicide increased the negative effects of thermal stress on coral at 31°C and 32°C. Mixed model analyses of variance showed that the effects of elevated sea surface temperatures (SST) and herbicide on photosynthetic efficiency of coral symbionts were additive. Furthermore, the effect of either diuron or atrazine in combination with higher SST (31°C and 32°C) on chronic photoinhibition was distinctly greater than additive (synergistic). Reducing the herbicide concentration by 1 μg L-1 diuron above 30°C would protect photosynthetic efficiency by the equivalent of 1.8°C and reduce chronic photoinhibition by the equivalent of a 1°C reduction. Reduced water quality increases the vulnerability of corals to elevated SSTs, and effective management of local water quality can reduce negative effects of global stressors such as elevated SST. © 2011, by the American Society of Limnology and Oceanography, Inc.",,"climate change; concentration (composition); coral; coral bleaching; environmental stress; numerical model; photoinhibition; photosynthesis; red alga; sea surface temperature; temperature effect; vulnerability; water quality; Acropora millepora; algae; Anthozoa; Neogoniolithon fosliei",,,,,,"(2010) Sea Temperature Monitoring Program [Internet], , http://www.aims.gov.au/docs/data-centre/seatemperatures.html, AIMS (AUSTRALIAN INSTITUTE OF MARINE SCIENCE), Townsville, Australia: Australian Institute of Marine Science [accessed 2010 December 14]; Anthony, K.R.N., Connolly, S.R., Hoegh-Guldberg, O., Bleaching, energetics, and coral mortality risk: Effects of temperature, light, and sediment regime (2007) Limnology and Oceanography, 52 (2), pp. 716-726; Kline, D.I., Diaz-Pulido, G., Dove, S., Hoeghguldberg, O., Ocean acidification causes bleaching and productivity loss in coral reef builders (2008) Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci., 105, pp. 17442-17446. , doi:10.1073/pnas.0804478105; Baird, A.H., Marshall, P.A., Mortality, growth and reproduction in scleractinian corals following bleaching on the Great Barrier Reef (2002) Mar. Ecol. Prog. Ser., 237, pp. 133-141. , doi:10.3354/meps237133; Bellwood, D.R., Hughes, T.P., Folke, C., Nystrom, M., Confronting the coral reef crisis (2004) Nature, 429 (6994), pp. 827-833. , DOI 10.1038/nature02691; Berkelmans, R., Van Oppen, M.J.H., The role of zooxanthellae in the thermal tolerance of corals: A 'nugget of hope' for coral reefs in an era of climate change (2006) Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences, 273 (1599), pp. 2305-2312. , DOI 10.1098/rspb.2006.3567; Berkelmans, R., Willis, B.L., Seasonal and 